            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Heather Erickson\u2019s story is a testament to quiet ambition. Raised in Portland, Oregon, by a high school history teacher and a dental hygienist, her upbringing was comfortable, stable, and deeply rooted in Pacific Northwest practicality. While she loved her family, Heather felt a pull toward a faster, more dynamic world. She attended the University of Washington, earning a degree in Communications, and took a product marketing job in Seattle\u2019s burgeoning tech scene. It was there, at 28, that she hit her first major wall: she was passed over for a promotion, with feedback that she lacked strategic business acumen.\n\nThis setback became her catalyst. Refusing to be sidelined, Heather channeled her frustration into action. She rigorously studied for the GMAT and was accepted into UC Berkeley's Haas School of Business. Moving to the Bay Area for her MBA was not just a career move; it was a reinvention. She thrived in the competitive environment, graduating with honors and a clear career trajectory.\n\nPost-MBA, Heather\u2019s ascent was steady and impressive. She navigated her way from Product Manager to Senior PM, and finally to her current role as Director of Product Management at a successful analytics firm in SoMa. Her success, however, came with personal costs. A seven-year relationship frayed under the pressure of her demanding career, ending when her partner wanted to move to the suburbs and start a family\u2014a life Heather wasn't ready to embrace.\n\nNow at 40, her life is a meticulously organized routine. Mornings start with a pre-dawn spin class before she catches the 8:15 AM company shuttle from her chic Hayes Valley apartment. Her days are a cascade of strategy meetings, team management, and product roadmaps. Weekends are for decompressing: hiking in the Marin Headlands, trying new tasting menus with a close circle of fellow professionals, and quiet evenings with a book. While she eyes a future VP role, a new question has begun to surface: what comes after? The dream is no longer just about the next title, but about finding a deeper sense of purpose, perhaps leveraging her skills to consult for non-profits or taking a long-overdue sabbatical to travel the world on her own terms."
